te about the European genocide from a distance, each chapter contains a compassionate and thoughtful analysis of the author’s individual opus, accompanied by a comprehensive exploration of their biography and the major themes that underpin their corpus. The rich and sophisticated discussions and interpretations contained in this masterful set of essays are sure to become essential reading for those seeking to better understand the responses by Hebrew writers to the immense tragedy that befell their people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945), in literature. 0aIsraeli literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  aAharon Appelfeld.  aDan Pagis.  aEtgar Keret.  aHolocaust remembrance.  aHolocaust.  aIsrael.  aIsraeli culture.  aIsraeli literature.  aJewish literature.  aKa-Tzetnik.  aUri Tzvi Greenberg.  aYoram Kaniuk.  agenocide.  ahistory.  amemory.  asurvivors.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311068819140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781644690055zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781644690055423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781644690055/original  a978-3-11-068819-1  Academic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK